### `canonNormalized`

**Signature:** `[ [IW](#iw) ] -> [ [FL](#fl) ] [ 8 ] -> Bit`

A field is normalized iff bytes at indices >= n are zero. This is the
invariant the C++ / Rust code maintains implicitly (it only reads the
first n bytes); making it explicit keeps logically-distinct requests
distinct as Cryptol values, so any collision the solver finds is a *real*
one.

and [ (i >= n) ==> ((b @ i) == 0)
        | i <- ([0 .. [FL](#fl) - 1] : [[FL](#fl)][[IW](#iw)]) ]

#### Related Properties
- [P23 — Canonicalization Injective](#p23--canonicalization-injective)
- [P24 — Header Canon Injective](#p24--header-canon-injective)
- [P25 — Query Canon Injective](#p25--query-canon-injective)

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
canonNormalized n b =
    and [ (i >= n) ==> ((b @ i) == 0)
        | i <- ([0 .. FL - 1] : [FL][IW]) ]
```

</details>

### `canonLenPrefixed`

**Signature:** `[ [IW](#iw) ] -> [ [FL](#fl) ] [ 8 ] -> [ [IW](#iw) ] -> [ [FL](#fl) ] [ 8 ] -> [ 2 * [FL](#fl) + 2 ] [ 8 ]`

Length-prefixed canonicalization. Each variable-length field is preceded
by its length tag: a parser reads the tag, then exactly that many bytes,
then the next tag, then exactly that many bytes. No byte inside any field
can be misread as a boundary, so the encoding is structurally injective.

The Cryptol bound uses an 8-bit length tag (sufficient for [FL](#fl) <= 255);
production uses a 64-bit big-endian tag (sufficient for any std::size_t /
usize field). The injectivity argument is identical for both widths.

[nm] # m # [nb] # b

#### Related Properties
- [P23 — Canonicalization Injective](#p23--canonicalization-injective)
- [P24 — Header Canon Injective](#p24--header-canon-injective)
- [P25 — Query Canon Injective](#p25--query-canon-injective)

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
canonLenPrefixed nm m nb b = [nm] # m # [nb] # b
```

</details>

### `fieldNormalized`

**Signature:** `[Field](#field) -> Bit`

(f.len <= (`[FLs](#fls) : [[IW](#iw)])) /\
  and [ (i >= f.len) ==> ((f.buf @ i) == 0)
      | i <- ([0 .. [FLs](#fls) - 1] : [[FLs](#fls)][[IW](#iw)]) ]

#### Related Properties
- [P28 — Auth Header Excluded](#p28--auth-header-excluded)

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
fieldNormalized f =
  (f.len <= (`FLs : [IW])) /\
  and [ (i >= f.len) ==> ((f.buf @ i) == 0)
      | i <- ([0 .. FLs - 1] : [FLs][IW]) ]
```

</details>

### `requestNormalized`

**Signature:** `[RequestS](#requests) -> Bit`

[fieldNormalized](#fieldnormalized) r.method /\
  [fieldNormalized](#fieldnormalized) r.path /\
  [fieldNormalized](#fieldnormalized) r.body /\
  and [ [fieldNormalized](#fieldnormalized) h.name /\ [fieldNormalized](#fieldnormalized) h.value
      | h <- r.hdrs ]

#### Related Properties
- [P28 — Auth Header Excluded](#p28--auth-header-excluded)

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
requestNormalized r =
  fieldNormalized r.method /\
  fieldNormalized r.path /\
  fieldNormalized r.body /\
  and [ fieldNormalized h.name /\ fieldNormalized h.value
      | h <- r.hdrs ]
```

</details>

### `lpField`

**Signature:** `[Field](#field) -> [ 1 + [FLs](#fls) ] [ 8 ]`

Length-prefix a [Field](#field) as [len-byte] # buf.

[f.len] # f.buf

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
lpField f = [f.len] # f.buf
```

</details>

### `lpHeader`

**Signature:** `[Header](#header) -> [ 2 * ( 1 + [FLs](#fls) ) ] [ 8 ]`

Length-prefix a header pair OR emit a constant-size all-zero placeholder
if it is the auth header. Fixed output size keeps [canonicalizeS](#canonicalizes) Cryptol-
statable; the placeholder content is irrelevant because the encoder
elides auth headers regardless of their value.

| # | Condition | Result |
|---|-----------|--------|
| 1 | h.isAuth | zero |
| 2 | *(otherwise)* | ([lpField](#lpfield) h.name) # ([lpField](#lpfield) h.value) |

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
lpHeader h = if h.isAuth then zero
                         else (lpField h.name) # (lpField h.value)
```

</details>

### `canonicalizeS`

**Signature:** `[RequestS](#requests) -> [ 3 * ( 1 + [FLs](#fls) ) + [Ns](#ns) * 2 * ( 1 + [FLs](#fls) ) + 8 ] [ 8 ]`

Concrete canonicalize: length-prefixed method, body, headers (with
auth-header exclusion), path, then the 8-byte big-endian timestamp.
Mirrors the production C++/Rust encoder shape.

[lpField](#lpfield) r.method
  # [lpField](#lpfield) r.body
  # join [ [lpHeader](#lpheader) h | h <- r.hdrs ]
  # [lpField](#lpfield) r.path
  # (split r.timestamp : [8][8])

#### Related Properties
- [P28 — Auth Header Excluded](#p28--auth-header-excluded)

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
canonicalizeS r =
    lpField r.method
  # lpField r.body
  # join [ lpHeader h | h <- r.hdrs ]
  # lpField r.path
  # (split r.timestamp : [8][8])
```

</details>

### `verifierTimestamp_current`

**Signature:** `[RequestS](#requests) -> [Timestamp](#timestamp) -> [Timestamp](#timestamp)`


The timestamp the verifier validates must equal the timestamp inside the
signed request — otherwise an attacker can replay a stale signed request
with a fresh "current time" supplied by the caller and pass the freshness
check despite the signature being over old bytes.

The implementation now binds the timestamp into the request: it is a
field of `DeviceRequest`, is included in the canonical signed bytes by
`canonicalizePayload`, and is the only value `handle_activate` passes
to `[isValidRequestDate](#isvalidrequestdate)`. The Cryptol model below mirrors that: the
verifier extracts `r.timestamp` and the caller-supplied parameter (if
any) is unused — a pure transport-layer artefact.

r.timestamp

#### Related Properties
- [P29 — Timestamp Bound](#p29--timestamp-bound)

<details><summary>Formal definition (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
verifierTimestamp_current r _ = r.timestamp
```

</details>

## Key Lifecycle Safety

### P1 — Key Monotonicity

[P1](#p1--key-monotonicity): Key Monotonicity. Once a key is active, any subsequent activation
attempt returns AlreadyActive. We model "the activation outcome when the
key is already active" as a function of the activation oracle; the spec
states this as an invariant on activationResult, which we express as:
for any inputs, if the system reports the key is active then [enrollDevice](#enrolldevice)
can never return Succeeded.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isAuthResult authResult ==>
keyAlreadyActive ==>
enrollDevice fleetEnabled validMetadata authResult AC_AlreadyActive
!= ER_Succeeded
```

</details>

### P2 — Active Prevents Provisioning

[P2](#p2--active-prevents-provisioning): Active prevents provisioning.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isKeyVaultResult vaultResult ==>
fleetEnabled ==>
validRequest ==>
vaultResult == KV_Ok ==>
provisionKey fleetEnabled validRequest vaultResult True
== PR_Unauthorized
```

</details>

### P3 — Key Id Hidden Until Active

[P3](#p3--key-id-hidden-until-active): Key ID hidden until active.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
(getStatus fleetEnabled hasKey False keyId).keyId == none
```

</details>

### P4 — Key Id Revealed When Active

[P4](#p4--key-id-revealed-when-active): Key ID revealed when active.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
(getStatus fleetEnabled hasKey True keyId).keyId == some keyId
```

</details>

### P5 — Disabled Rejects All

[P5](#p5--disabled-rejects-all): Disabled rejects all.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
authResult activationResult keyIsActive =
isKeyVaultResult vaultResult ==>
isAuthResult authResult ==>
isActivationResult activationResult ==>
(provisionKey False validRequest vaultResult keyIsActive == PR_Disabled)
&& (enrollDevice False validMetadata authResult activationResult
== ER_Disabled)
```

</details>

## Authentication Security

### P6 — Auth Requires Valid Date

[P6](#p6--auth-requires-valid-date): Auth requires valid date.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
authenticate False sigValid claimsValid == False
```

</details>

### P7 — Auth Requires Valid Signature

[P7](#p7--auth-requires-valid-signature): Auth requires valid signature.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
authenticate dateValid False claimsValid == False
```

</details>

### P8 — Correct Signature Verifies

[P8](#p8--correct-signature-verifies): Correct signature verifies.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isValidSignature k r (hmacSha256 k r) == True
```

</details>

### P9 — Wrong Signature Fails

[P9](#p9--wrong-signature-fails): Wrong signature fails.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
(sig != hmacSha256 k r) ==> (isValidSignature k r sig == False)
```

</details>

### P10 — Missing Metadata Fails

[P10](#p10--missing-metadata-fails): Missing metadata fails (when the fleet is enabled).
Note: when the fleet is disabled, [enrollDevice](#enrolldevice) short-circuits to
[ER_Disabled](#enrollmentresult) before the metadata check, so we restrict this property
to the fleetEnabled case. The disabled case is covered by [P5](#p5--disabled-rejects-all).

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
fleetEnabled ==>
isAuthResult authResult ==>
isActivationResult activationResult ==>
enrollDevice fleetEnabled False authResult activationResult
== ER_Unauthorized
```

</details>

## Access Control

### P11 — Off Mode Allows All

[P11](#p11--off-mode-allows-all): Off mode allows all (and logs nothing).

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isAccessDecision decision ==>
enforceAccess AM_Off decision == (True, False)
```

</details>

### P12 — Audit Never Denies

[P12](#p12--audit-never-denies): Audit mode never denies.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isAccessDecision decision ==>
(enforceAccess AM_Audit decision).0 == True
```

</details>

### P13 — Enforce Blocks Denied

[P13](#p13--enforce-blocks-denied): Enforce blocks denied.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
enforceAccess AM_Enforce AD_Deny == (False, True)
```

</details>

### P14 — Enforce Allows Permitted

[P14](#p14--enforce-allows-permitted): Enforce allows permitted.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
enforceAccess AM_Enforce AD_Allow == (True, False)
```

</details>

## Protocol Liveness

### P15 — Can Provision When Ready

[P15](#p15--can-provision-when-ready): Can provision when ready.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
provisionKey True True KV_Ok False == PR_Succeeded
```

</details>

### P16 — Authenticated Activation Succeeds

[P16](#p16--authenticated-activation-succeeds): Authenticated activation succeeds.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
enrollDevice True True AR_Authenticated AC_Success == ER_Succeeded
```

</details>

### P17 — Timestamp At Boundary Valid

[P17](#p17--timestamp-at-boundary-valid): [Timestamp](#timestamp) at boundary is valid.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
// Avoid 64-bit overflow when constructing currentTime.
(requestTs <= (~ zero) - window) ==>
isValidRequestDate requestTs (requestTs + window) window == True
```

</details>

### P18 — Timestamp Beyond Boundary Invalid

[P18](#p18--timestamp-beyond-boundary-invalid): [Timestamp](#timestamp) beyond boundary is invalid.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
(requestTs : Timestamp) (currentTime : Timestamp) (window : Window) =
(requestTs <= currentTime) ==>
((currentTime - requestTs) > window) ==>
isValidRequestDate requestTs currentTime window == False
```

</details>

## Error Handling

### P19 — Vault Unavailable Is Internal

[P19](#p19--vault-unavailable-is-internal): Vault unavailable is InternalError.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isActivationResult activationResult ==>
enrollDevice True True AR_VaultUnavailable activationResult
== ER_InternalError
```

</details>

### P20 — Bad Request Distinct

[P20](#p20--bad-request-distinct): BadRequest distinct from Unauthorized.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isKeyVaultResult vaultResult ==>
provisionKey True False vaultResult keyIsActive == PR_BadRequest
```

</details>

### P21 — Activate Without Metadata Unauthorized

[P21](#p21--activate-without-metadata-unauthorized): Activate without metadata is Unauthorized.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isAuthResult authResult ==>
isActivationResult activationResult ==>
enrollDevice True False authResult activationResult == ER_Unauthorized
```

</details>

### P22 — Activation Io Failure Is Internal

[P22](#p22--activation-io-failure-is-internal): Activation I/O failure is InternalError. An activation result that is
neither Success nor AlreadyActive (i.e. an I/O failure) must yield
InternalError when authentication succeeded.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isActivationResult activationResult ==>
(activationResult != AC_Success) ==>
(activationResult != AC_AlreadyActive) ==>
enrollDevice True True AR_Authenticated activationResult
== ER_InternalError
```

</details>

### P23 — Canonicalization Injective

[P23](#p23--canonicalization-injective): Length-prefixed canonicalization is byte-injective — distinct
normalized requests produce distinct canonical byte streams.
> **Note:** EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS. This is the safety property the production
> canonicalizer satisfies after the delimiter -> length-prefix fix.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
nm1 m1 nb1 b1 nm2 m2 nb2 b2 =
( (nm1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\ (nb1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\
(nm2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\ (nb2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\
canonNormalized nm1 m1 /\ canonNormalized nb1 b1 /\
canonNormalized nm2 m2 /\ canonNormalized nb2 b2 /\
canonLenPrefixed nm1 m1 nb1 b1 == canonLenPrefixed nm2 m2 nb2 b2 )
==> ((nm1, m1, nb1, b1) == (nm2, m2, nb2, b2))
```

</details>

### P24 — Header Canon Injective

//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
6.b Sub-canonicalizer injectivity — Tier-1 follow-up to [P23](#p23--canonicalization-injective).

The [P23](#p23--canonicalization-injective) fix length-prefixes the FIVE TOP-LEVEL fields of the canonical
payload (method | body | canonHeaders | path | canonQuery). The inner
canonicalizers `canonicalize_headers` and `canonicalize_query` now use
the SAME length-prefix scheme for every individual name and value they
emit (an 8-byte big-endian length tag followed by the raw bytes), so
they are structurally byte-injective in their input map by the same
argument that proves [P23](#p23--canonicalization-injective): a parser reads <tag, name, tag, value> in
fixed order with no byte inside any name or value capable of being
misread as a record boundary.

Historical note: an earlier revision joined records with '\n' (headers)
or '&' (query) and fields inside each record with ':' / '='. That
encoding admitted a header / query smuggling collision (a value
containing "\nname:forged" parsed as an extra record under a forged
header name). Concrete production-code collisions for that earlier
encoding were exhibited in rust/tests/validate_canon_gaps.rs.
//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
[P24](#p24--header-canon-injective): `canonicalize_headers` is byte-injective in the header map.
The production encoder length-prefixes every name and value with an
8-byte big-endian tag (same shape as canonicalizePayload), so distinct
normalized header records produce distinct canonical byte streams.
> **Note:** EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS — the encoding closes the smuggling gap.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
( (nm1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\ (nb1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\
(nm2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\ (nb2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\
canonNormalized nm1 m1 /\ canonNormalized nb1 b1 /\
canonNormalized nm2 m2 /\ canonNormalized nb2 b2 /\
canonLenPrefixed nm1 m1 nb1 b1 == canonLenPrefixed nm2 m2 nb2 b2 )
==> ((nm1, m1, nb1, b1) == (nm2, m2, nb2, b2))
```

</details>

### P25 — Query Canon Injective

[P25](#p25--query-canon-injective): `canonicalize_query` is byte-injective in the query map.
Same length-prefix shape; no separators are needed because the length
tag uniquely marks each record boundary.
> **Note:** EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
( (nm1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\ (nb1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\
(nm2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\ (nb2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\
canonNormalized nm1 m1 /\ canonNormalized nb1 b1 /\
canonNormalized nm2 m2 /\ canonNormalized nb2 b2 /\
canonLenPrefixed nm1 m1 nb1 b1 == canonLenPrefixed nm2 m2 nb2 b2 )
==> ((nm1, m1, nb1, b1) == (nm2, m2, nb2, b2))
```

</details>

### P26 — Enforce No Rule Allows Silently

//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
6.c [enforceAccess](#enforceaccess) matrix-coverage gap — Tier-3 follow-up.

[P11](#p11--off-mode-allows-all)..[P14](#p14--enforce-allows-permitted) cover only 5 of the 9 cells of the ([AccessMode](#accessmode) × [AccessDecision](#accessdecision))
matrix, and [P12](#p12--audit-never-denies) only checks the `.0 = allowed` projection (not the
`.1 = logged` flag). The two properties below close the matrix.
> **Note:** EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS — they document previously-unverified behaviour
> of the existing model.
> //////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
> [P26](#p26--enforce-no-rule-allows-silently): Enforce mode with no matching rule allows silently (matches the
> spec's implicit fall-through and the C++/Rust impl's `else` branch).

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
enforceAccess AM_Enforce AD_NoRule == (True, False)
```

</details>

### P27 — Audit Logged Only On Deny

[P27](#p27--audit-logged-only-on-deny): Audit mode logs IFF the underlying decision is Deny — never on
Allow or NoRule. Closes the .1 = logged projection that [P12](#p12--audit-never-denies) leaves
unspecified.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
isAccessDecision decision ==>
(enforceAccess AM_Audit decision).1 == (decision == AD_Deny)
```

</details>

## Auth-header exclusion

### P28 — Auth Header Excluded


Two requests that differ ONLY in the bytes of their auth header value
must produce the same canonical bytes — otherwise the signature would
depend on itself.

> **Note:** EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS. The encoder's `isAuth` skip enforces this; if a
> future refactor removes the skip, this property breaks immediately.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
( requestNormalized r /\ fieldNormalized v1 /\ fieldNormalized v2 ) ==>
canonicalizeS { r | hdrs = [ if h.isAuth then { h | value = v1 } else h
| h <- r.hdrs ] }
==
canonicalizeS { r | hdrs = [ if h.isAuth then { h | value = v2 } else h
| h <- r.hdrs ] }
```

</details>

## Timestamp binding

### P29 — Timestamp Bound

> **Note:** EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS — the verifier uses the request-bound timestamp,
> so a replayed signed request cannot be paired with a fresh "current
> time" parameter to forge freshness.

<details><summary>Formal property (Cryptol)</summary>

```cryptol
verifierTimestamp_current r tsFromCaller == r.timestamp
```

</details>
